				 Besu, Belfast varsity tie up
 AMIT ROY 																								London, Nov. 18: Northern Irelands economy is to be driven forward by science and technology students from India under an agreement between the prestigious Queens University in Belfast and Bengal Engineering and Science University, Shibpur.																								The deal on the scholarship programme, to be formally announced tomorrow, follows 10 days of talks in India with a visiting team of senior Northern Ireland academics.																								The Indian students will live in Belfast and study at the Institute of Electronics, Communications and Information Technology, a world-class research centre at Queens.																								Chris Gibson, pro-chancellor of Queens, explained why collaboration with India was essential. Today the demands on a university go beyond producing skilled graduates and world-class research, he said in a statement.																								Universities are now recognised as the drivers of economic development, an essential prerequisite for a knowledge-based economy. Queens partnership with India will assist with this economic development.																								Gibson added: The opportunities for collaboration include split site studentships, staff exchanges and research partnerships.																								An agreement has also been signed between Queens and the Indian biotechnology ministry. It involves top cancer specialists from the National Institute of Immunology, New Delhi, and the Centre for Cancer Research and Cell Biology at Queens. 
